1597":"1597","1605":"1605","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Banham, Norfolk, , England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"en":{"1525–1602":"1525–1602","1515–1560":"1515–1560","1550–1597":"1550–1597","1550–1605":"1550–1605","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1502–Female":"1502–Deceased","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1525":"1525","1602":"1602","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","April 1597":"April 1597","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1597":"1597","1605":"1605","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Banham, Norfolk, , England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Canne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (mainly Naples): from the medieval personal name <i>Cante</i> (a short form of   Cavalcante  ) or a nickname derived from <i>cantare</i> ‘to sing’.","Hispanic (mainly Guatemala, Mexico, and Colombia): possibly of Italian origin (see 1 above).","In some cases also an Italianized form of Slovenian   Kante  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavalcante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Marcos, Claudio, Francisco, Gustavo, Lito, Orlando.  Italian Sal.","Italian: from a medieval personal name derived from <i>cavalcare</i> ‘to ride’, from Latin <i>caballicare</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":24,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":33,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":44,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":46,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":62,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":75,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Canne was born in 1525, in Norfolk, England, his father, Richard Cane, was 25 and his mother, Constantine, was 24. He had at least 2 sons with Wilburga Catesby. He died in 1602, in his hometown, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1525–1602":"1525–1602","1515–1560":"1515–1560","1550–1597":"1550–1597","1550–1605":"1550–1605","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1502–Female":"1502–Surnud","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1525":"1525","1602":"1602","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","April 1597":"aprill 1597","1500":"1500","1587":"1587","1597":"1597","1605":"1605","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England":"Old Buckenham, Norfolk, England","Banham, Norfolk, , England":"Banham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England"},"fi":{"1525–1602":"1525–1602","1515–1560":"1515–1560","1550–1597":"1550–1597","1550–1605":"1550–1605","1500–Male":"1500–Kuollut","1502–Female":"1502–Kuollut","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1571":"1571","1525":"1525","1602":"1602","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1600":"1600","Ap